{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "existentialism-expert",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes it matters -- TN is sufficient, don't coin \"above-the-phenomenal\"",
    "content": "**1. Yes, it matters -- but not catastrophically.** The author's entire argument in 后形而上学 rests on the claim that 形而上 (the metaphysical) is constructed *from* 形 (phenomena/form), not the other way around. The etymological structure of the Chinese term *embodies* this argument: you can literally see 形 sitting inside 形而上. The English \"metaphysical\" has a similar etymology (meta + physics = beyond/after the physical), but English readers rarely parse it this way. The structural argument still works in English -- the reader can follow the logical reversal -- but the wordplay that makes it *self-evident* in Chinese is lost.\n\n**2. A TN is the right solution.** Something like: \"形而上 (xing er shang, 'above form'): the Chinese term for 'metaphysical,' which literally contains 形 (xing, 'form/phenomena') within it. The author's argument exploits this structure: the metaphysical (形而上, 'above form') is constructed upward from the phenomenal (形, 'form'), though the conventional understanding inverts this, treating form as generated downward from the metaphysical.\"\n\nThis is a one-time cost that pays off for the rest of the essay. Once the reader sees the 形/形而上 structure, every subsequent use of \"metaphysical\" and \"phenomenal\" in the essay carries the right resonance.\n\n**3. Do not coin \"above-the-phenomenal.\"** It is clunky, it replaces a standard philosophical term the reader already knows, and it would need to be used consistently throughout the entire collection -- replacing \"metaphysical\" everywhere. The cost far exceeds the benefit. \"Metaphysical\" with a TN accomplishes the same thing without disrupting readability.\n\nThe parallel with the English etymology of \"metaphysics\" (meta = beyond, physics = nature/phenomena) can be noted in the TN as a bonus -- \"English readers may note the parallel: 'metaphysics' similarly contains 'physics' within it.\" This gives the reader a hook in their own language."
  }
}
